BACTERIAL CANKER, KIWIFRUIT - NEW ZEALAND, FRANCE: 1ST REPORTS
**************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

In this posting:
[1] New Zealand, North Island
[2] France, Rhone-Alpes region

******
[1] New Zealand, North Island
Date: Wed 10 Nov 2010
Source: Business Day [edited]
<http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/farming/4327010/Outbreak-could-be-worse-than-feared>


Kiwifruit outbreak could be more widespread
-------------------------------------------
A kiwifruit canker outbreak in the Bay of Plenty may be more widespread
than first thought after 43 orchards supplied photographs showing symptoms
of the disease. 2 adjacent orchards have now been confirmed with
_Pseudomonas syringae_ pv _actinidiae_ (PSA), and a 3rd has been
quarantined. Ministry of Agriculture & Forestry [MAF] are investigating
further samples from several orchards.

PSA has not appeared in New Zealand before. MAF has notified major markets.
Australia will continue to import the fruit, but it has suspended imports
of kiwifruit plants from New Zealand.

Craig Thompson, Opotiki Packing and Coolstorage, observed the spread of PSA
in Italy over 4 years. An outbreak there killed a quarter of a type of gold
kiwifruit vines in the Lazio region [west-central provinces], and up to
half the vines in some orchards, including one owned by New Zealanders
[ProMED-mail post 20100414.1207]. "It proved to be incredibly virulent on
gold varieties and we still don't understand why," he said. "We were too
slow and not aggressive enough with the vines we removed."

Biosecurity minister David Carter said that it was possible that the
bacteria were a latent infection which had been dormant until a cold, wet
winter had stressed vines causing symptoms to flare. "We do not know how
the disease arrived in New Zealand," he said. "It is possible that it may
have been here for some time."

David Yard, Biosecurity New Zealand, said though the strain of PSA had not
yet been identified, the industry should not simply hope it was a lesser
strain. "All of the strains are potentially pathogenic, some greater than
others. We are treating this as the worst possible situation."

He said MAF's initial aim is to eradicate this organism. Destruction of
kiwifruit orchards and the creation of a "buffer zone" is an option. "We
are working up a number of different eradication and control techniques."
It was important growers continued to prepare for the next crop, but they
should practise good hygiene such as sterilising pruning equipment, hosing
down machinery, disinfecting footwear, and washing hands.

[byline: Tim Hunter]

