******
[2] France, Rhone-Alpes region
Date: October 2010
Source: European Plant Protection Organisation (EPPO) Reporting Service
10/2010/188 [edited]
<http://archives.eppo.org/EPPOReporting/2010/Rse-1010.pdf>


1st record of _Pseudomonas syringae_ pv. _actinidiae_ in France
---------------------------------------------------------------
The NPPO [National Plant Protection Organisation] of France recently
informed the EPPO Secretariat of the 1st detection of _Pseudomonas
syringae_ pv. _actinidiae_ (EPPO Alert List) on its territory. The
bacterium was identified on 26 Jul 2010 in 5 samples of _Actinidia
deliciosa_ cv. 'Summer' (green kiwifruit) which had been collected from
Rhone-Alpes region. This outbreak concerned 4 plots of cv. 'Summer' but
similar symptoms have been observed in another plot of cv. 'Hayward' where
samples are currently being tested.

All infected plants originated from a single lot imported from a nursery of
another EPPO member country. The NPPO of this country was informed
immediately. The possible phytosanitary measures which could be taken are
currently being studied by the French NPPO. Tracing-back studies are being
carried out to determine if other plants had been imported from the
infected nursery. In addition, surveys will be conducted at the beginning
of 2011 to determine the extent of bacterial canker of kiwifruit in France.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Bacterial canker of kiwifruit (_Actinidia_ species and hybrids) caused by
_Pseudomonas syringae_ pv. _actinidiae_ was originally described in Japan
in 1989, but its area of origin is uncertain. Symptoms include
discolouration of buds and vascular tissues, leaf spots, wilting, stem and
twig cankers with characteristic red exudate, fruit collapse, and
eventually death of the plant. The disease is favoured by cool temperatures
and high humidity, thus symptoms are usually seen in spring and autumn.

Data on epidemiology are still lacking, but infection is thought to occur
via natural leaf openings and wounds. The pathogen is suspected to be
spread by heavy rain, strong winds, mechanical means (including animal and
human activities), and infected planting material. Spread with infected
fruit cannot be excluded. Generally, disease management of bacterial
diseases may include cultural practices, crop rotation, phytosanitation to
prevent spread, and use of clean planting material and resistant crop
varieties, but specific control strategies for kiwi canker are being
developed. Chemical control (copper compounds, antibiotics) is used in
Japan, but resistant pathogen strains have emerged.

It is thought that a recent outbreak in Italy (ProMED-mail post
20100414.1207) affecting 25 per cent of the Zespri Gold variety vines may
have been due to the emergence of a new strain.

We are most grateful to Mr TJ Allen for supplying a number of the news
stories listed below.

